50|$|When Japan {{became a}} member of the OECD in 1966, it agreed to liberalise its capital markets. This process began in 1967 and continues. <b>Decontrol</b> <b>of</b> {{international}} capital flows was aided in 1980, when the new Foreign Exchange and Foreign Control Law went into effect. In principle, all external economic transactions were free of control, unless specified otherwise. In practice, a wide range of transactions continued to be subject to some form of formal or informal control by the government.|$|R
